WEBVTT

00:03.620 --> 00:05.580
Meredith: The poet Octavio Paz
once wrote,

00:05.580 --> 00:07.880
"The Mexican is familiar
with death.

00:07.880 --> 00:10.120
Jokes about it. Caresses it.

00:10.120 --> 00:12.620
Sleeps with it. Celebrates it."

00:12.620 --> 00:14.580
It's called
Day of the Dead.

00:14.580 --> 00:16.460
Tyler said it's like
a Mexican Halloween,

00:16.460 --> 00:18.330
but he's wrong.

00:18.330 --> 00:20.420
I can relate.
♪ In my heart ♪

00:20.420 --> 00:21.830
♪ Lightning strikes ♪
[ Blender whirring ]

00:21.830 --> 00:24.170
But in a hospital,
death isn't celebrated.

00:24.170 --> 00:25.790
It's avoided at all costs.

00:25.790 --> 00:27.790
♪ This is my, this is my,
this is my life ♪

00:27.790 --> 00:29.380
It's like the one day
of the year

00:29.380 --> 00:31.210
where the people
who you love that died

00:31.210 --> 00:32.710
come back
to be with you.

00:32.710 --> 00:33.920
Not like zombies.

00:33.920 --> 00:35.210
More like spirits.

00:35.210 --> 00:36.750
But not ghosts.

00:36.750 --> 00:39.420
And when it comes...
Angels? I don't know.

00:39.420 --> 00:41.420
...it's clinical,
almost routine.

00:41.420 --> 00:43.420
Today in homeroom,
we're making these big altars,

00:43.420 --> 00:44.880
like offerings
for the dead.

00:44.880 --> 00:46.120
♪ It's a good day ♪

00:46.120 --> 00:47.960
♪ It's a good, good life ♪

00:47.960 --> 00:49.460
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

00:49.460 --> 00:51.420
But still,
with all that practice,

00:51.420 --> 00:53.500
even surgeons
are surprised by death.

00:53.500 --> 00:55.420
[ Whispering ]
Three, two, one.

00:55.420 --> 00:57.710
[ Together ] Hola!
[ Chuckles ]

00:57.710 --> 01:01.750
You guys look so beautiful --
and scary.

01:01.750 --> 01:04.540
It's not supposed to be scary.
It's Dia de los Muertos.

01:04.540 --> 01:06.920
We're doing
a parade at school.
[ Gasps ] So cool!

01:06.920 --> 01:09.500
Especially when it happens
to the ones we love.

01:09.500 --> 01:12.040
Another date for you?
Cece is too good at her job.

01:12.040 --> 01:14.170
[ Chuckling ]
Who is it this time?

01:14.170 --> 01:17.170
Uh, Daniel,
who's an English teacher.

01:17.170 --> 01:19.290
Or a professor. I'm not
really sure which one.

01:19.290 --> 01:21.710
There's a big difference.
You should find out.

01:21.710 --> 01:23.330
Okay, girls,
we should get going.

01:23.330 --> 01:24.580
♪ I'm dreaming out,
dreaming out ♪

01:24.580 --> 01:26.080
♪ Dreaming out loud ♪

01:26.080 --> 01:28.290
[ Chuckles ]
♪ Right now is a good time ♪

01:28.290 --> 01:30.080
I'll see you in a bit.
-See you.

01:30.080 --> 01:31.790
Oh, I almost forgot
to tell you.

01:31.790 --> 01:33.210
I just got a text
from Teddy.

01:33.210 --> 01:35.790
She's planning
to speak to Owen today.

01:35.790 --> 01:39.210
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪
[ Door opens and closes ]

01:39.210 --> 01:42.420
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪
I'll believe it when I see it.

01:42.420 --> 01:44.000
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

01:44.000 --> 01:45.380
[ Sighs heavily ]

01:45.380 --> 01:46.750
♪ I'm alive, I'm alive ♪

01:46.750 --> 01:48.580
[ Doorbell rings ]

01:48.580 --> 01:50.880
♪ I'm alive, I'm alive ♪
Hi.

01:50.880 --> 01:52.080
♪ It's a good day ♪
Hi.

01:52.080 --> 01:53.960
Come in.

01:53.960 --> 01:55.670
Thank you
for doing this.

01:55.670 --> 01:57.620
It's fine.

01:57.620 --> 01:59.750
What brings you...
back to town?

01:59.750 --> 02:01.460
Is, uh --
Is Amelia home?

02:01.460 --> 02:04.040
No, but she knows
that you're here.
Okay, good, good. Yeah.

02:04.040 --> 02:06.290
What's going on, Teddy?

02:06.290 --> 02:07.790
I, um...

02:07.790 --> 02:13.210
♪♪

02:13.210 --> 02:16.210
I'm -- I'm sorry,
uh, about last month

02:16.210 --> 02:17.830
and just how rude I was
and that I --

02:17.830 --> 02:19.790
I left without
any kind of explanation.

02:19.790 --> 02:21.790
I just -- It's been a really
confusing last few months.

02:21.790 --> 02:23.710
Listen, it's fine.

02:23.710 --> 02:26.210
It's me, Teddy. You don't
have to apologize to me.

02:26.210 --> 02:28.670
In fact, I should be the one
apologizing to you.
Owen, I just -- Oh.

02:28.670 --> 02:30.920
[ Door opens ]
Betty?
Betty, are you here?!

02:30.920 --> 02:32.750
Uh, no.
You drove her to school.

02:32.750 --> 02:35.250
Yeah, and then I took
Leo to daycare, and
then the school called

02:35.250 --> 02:37.040
and they said that
she never showed up.

02:37.040 --> 02:38.380
Owen: Okay, then let's call her.
Hi.
Teddy: Hi.

02:38.380 --> 02:39.330
I tried, Owen.
Her phone is off,

02:39.330 --> 02:41.750
I can't track her,
I cannot see her texts.

02:41.750 --> 02:44.330
She doesn't want us
to find her.
Okay.
Well, let's search the park.

02:44.330 --> 02:46.330
That's where she goes
with her friends, right?
To do drugs, probably.

02:46.330 --> 02:48.040
She's not doing drugs.
[ Sighs ] Not yet.

02:48.040 --> 02:49.380
We're gonna find her.
It's gonna be okay.

02:49.380 --> 02:51.580
I'm sorry.
Can we, uh, talk later?

02:51.580 --> 02:52.920
-Yeah. Of course.
-Thanks.

02:52.920 --> 02:54.290
Um, I-I can help you
look for her.

02:54.290 --> 02:56.170
Thank you.
Yeah.

02:58.330 --> 02:59.750
So, lunch later?

02:59.750 --> 03:02.710
Well, I have a budget meeting
and then a, uh,

03:02.710 --> 03:06.080
briefing from legal, and then,
um, I'm in surgery.

03:06.080 --> 03:08.420
Oh, hey, can you post
a flier or something

03:08.420 --> 03:10.790
reminding the residents
and the interns to vote?

03:10.790 --> 03:13.420
I am not chief resident anymore.
I am a fellow.

03:13.420 --> 03:14.580
[ Elevator bell dings ]
Crap. I knew that.

03:14.580 --> 03:16.580
[ Chuckles ]
So, who is, then?

03:16.580 --> 03:18.580
Shouldn't the chief
know that?

03:18.580 --> 03:21.670
I -- I'm gonna post
a flier.

03:21.670 --> 03:23.880
[ Chuckles ]
Mmmmmwah!

03:23.880 --> 03:26.750
Thanks.
[ Chuckles ]
Best chief ever!

03:26.750 --> 03:28.670
[ Woman on P.A.
speaking indistinctly ]

03:28.670 --> 03:30.710
Such a good interim
First Lady.

03:30.710 --> 03:33.580
[ Scoffs ] I'm trying.
He's grumpy all the time.

03:33.580 --> 03:35.080
You sure that's
not just marriage?
[ Scoffs ]

03:35.080 --> 03:37.170
Just 'cause
you're scared of it.

03:37.170 --> 03:39.670
I'm not afraid of anything
but global warming.

03:39.670 --> 03:42.750
Oh, you know who's single?
Meredith.
Grey?

03:42.750 --> 03:44.460
Mm-hmm.
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah, no, she's not into me.

03:44.460 --> 03:45.830
Well, not yet.

03:45.830 --> 03:47.460
Listen, I know that
you look like that,

03:47.460 --> 03:49.750
so you're not used to having to,
like, put in the work.

03:49.750 --> 03:51.330
[ Cellphone chimes ]
Yeah, women usually
just feed me the grapes.

03:51.330 --> 03:53.880
Pft.
[ Chuckling ] Shut up.
You started it.

03:53.880 --> 03:56.120
Yes.
My liver patient's here.

03:56.120 --> 03:58.380
I'm doing my first solo
transplant surgery today.

03:58.380 --> 04:00.000
All right, knock 'em dead.
Yeah.

04:00.000 --> 04:01.290
Er...
Mnh-mnh.

04:01.290 --> 04:03.170
Not dead, but --
You know what I mean.
Thanks.

04:03.170 --> 04:05.210
Oh, and, um --
and, Link, uh,

04:05.210 --> 04:07.420
Meredith is a tough nut
to crack,

04:07.420 --> 04:09.920
but she's worth it.

04:09.920 --> 04:12.880
Dr. Lincoln, I believe
I'm on your service today.

04:14.000 --> 04:15.380
Oh, cool.

04:15.380 --> 04:17.750
Uh, we got a pip-squeak
with a broken arm.

04:17.750 --> 04:18.790
Nice and easy.

04:18.790 --> 04:20.960
♪♪

04:20.960 --> 04:23.580
What's up?
I've just...

04:23.580 --> 04:25.710
never done ortho before.

04:25.710 --> 04:27.580
I'll show you.
[ Elevator bell dings ]

04:27.580 --> 04:30.330
[ Chuckles ]

04:30.330 --> 04:32.380
No organ music, okay?

04:32.380 --> 04:35.290
I want the deli platter
from the good deli,

04:35.290 --> 04:37.250
and everyone should wear black.
Don't listen to my brother,

04:37.250 --> 04:38.420
who says you're all
gonna wear white.

04:38.420 --> 04:40.580
In fact, kick him out
if he wears white.

04:40.580 --> 04:43.330
I want Sicilian-widow-level
mourning.

04:43.330 --> 04:44.880
Can you smack some sense
into her?

04:44.880 --> 04:46.790
Hi. Denise. Best friend.

04:46.790 --> 04:48.460
Hi.
Hi, Denise.

04:48.460 --> 04:50.170
Uh, Roberta,

04:50.170 --> 04:52.620
you know we brought you in here
because we have a liver for you.

04:52.620 --> 04:54.460
It's on its way as we speak.
I know.

04:54.460 --> 04:57.330
I've been burned before.
This time I'm prepared.

04:57.330 --> 04:58.670
She wants me to cry,

04:58.670 --> 05:00.790
but I'm not giving her
the satisfaction.

05:00.790 --> 05:03.250
Go ahead.
Roberta Gibbs, 45 years old,

05:03.250 --> 05:04.960
was born
with Wilson's disease,

05:04.960 --> 05:07.170
has received multiple
chelation treatments,

05:07.170 --> 05:09.040
and had a TIPS
procedure last year.

05:09.040 --> 05:11.540
She is scheduled
for a liver transplant.

05:11.540 --> 05:14.460
Which I probably won't get.
Would you stop?

05:14.460 --> 05:17.210
Dr. Bailey.
UNOS is on the phone.

05:17.210 --> 05:18.920
See?
Wh-- [ Scoffs ]

05:18.920 --> 05:21.000
They're probably calling
to say the liver's ready.

05:21.000 --> 05:22.880
No. I know that look.

05:22.880 --> 05:24.830
That's the "the liver
got diverted" look.

05:27.750 --> 05:30.420
I'm sorry.

05:35.290 --> 05:38.960
Okay, uh, none of this comedy
roast, "sing a funny song" crap.

05:38.960 --> 05:41.790
I want a proper funeral,
where everybody's crying.

05:41.790 --> 05:43.380
[ Guitar playing
"En El último Trago" ]

05:43.380 --> 05:44.790
Write that down.

05:44.790 --> 05:49.500
♪ Tómate esta botella conmigo ♪

05:49.500 --> 05:54.420
♪ Y en el último trago
nos vamos ♪

05:54.420 --> 05:59.120
♪ Quiero ver a que sabe
tu olvido ♪

05:59.120 --> 06:03.960
♪ Sin poner mis ojos
tus manos ♪

06:03.960 --> 06:05.330
Hello, Medina family.
Oh.

06:05.330 --> 06:07.500
Are we having a party?
[ Laughter ]

06:07.500 --> 06:08.880
It's Dia de los Muertos.

06:08.880 --> 06:10.210
It's a very important day
for us,

06:10.210 --> 06:11.750
but they all wanted to be here
for my daughter.

06:11.750 --> 06:13.210
So, we built our own ofrenda.

06:13.210 --> 06:14.420
I hope it's okay.

06:14.420 --> 06:15.500
Meredith: Hello, hello.
Of course.

06:15.500 --> 06:16.540
Hey.

06:16.540 --> 06:18.580
Laura: Who's this?
I'm Dr. Grey.

06:18.580 --> 06:20.210
Alex: Dr. Grey is here
to help us today.

06:20.210 --> 06:21.620
You're the chief.

06:21.620 --> 06:24.000
You can't take out a gallbladder
by yourself?

06:24.000 --> 06:25.670
I can, but, uh,

06:25.670 --> 06:28.790
Flor needs more than a simple
gallbladder removal.

06:28.790 --> 06:31.040
Meredith:
After studying her scans,
we've determined that Flor

06:31.040 --> 06:34.040
has a choledochal cyst
in her biliary system.

06:34.040 --> 06:35.670
A cyst?
But don't worry. It's benign.

06:35.670 --> 06:38.120
A cyst? Where? In her belly?
Let me see.

06:38.120 --> 06:39.920
[ Whispering ] Mami. Stop.
Meredith: The cyst is in
her common bile duct...

06:39.920 --> 06:41.960
[ Whispering ] I'm sorry.
And it does need to come out
as soon as possible

06:41.960 --> 06:44.330
because it can lead to
the growth of cancerous cells.

06:44.330 --> 06:46.670
But we're gonna take
that out and reduce
that risk to zero.

06:46.670 --> 06:49.960
We do a procedure called
a Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy.

06:49.960 --> 06:52.250
Did you just make that up?
[ Laughter ]

06:52.250 --> 06:53.580
It's a procedure where
we attach

06:53.580 --> 06:55.580
a piece of your intestine
to your biliary tract.

06:55.580 --> 06:58.170
Can everyone please stop talking
about my biliary tract?

06:58.170 --> 06:59.500
I'm sorry.
We're almost done.

06:59.500 --> 07:01.670
Laura: Is my baby gonna be okay?
Alex: Yes. She is.

07:01.670 --> 07:03.920
It's a longer surgery
than we originally planned,

07:03.920 --> 07:05.540
but we're gonna take
good care of her.

07:05.540 --> 07:07.580
Meredith: So, Dr. DeLuca
will take her upstairs

07:07.580 --> 07:10.380
and prep her for surgery.
We're gonna repeat her LFTs.
Okay.

07:10.380 --> 07:11.920
It's very nice
to meet all of you.

07:11.920 --> 07:13.540
Thank you, Doctor.
Gracias.
Thank you.

07:15.290 --> 07:16.460
Can we talk?

07:17.750 --> 07:19.500
Is everything okay?

07:23.170 --> 07:25.540
When's the last time
you spoke to your dad?

07:25.540 --> 07:28.790
Thatcher?
Uh, when Lexie died, I guess.

07:28.790 --> 07:30.460
Yeah.

07:30.460 --> 07:32.290
Why?

07:32.290 --> 07:35.750
Um...

07:35.750 --> 07:37.620
He's sick, Meredith.

07:37.620 --> 07:39.710
His liver?
Is he drinking again?

07:39.710 --> 07:41.670
No, he's still sober.

07:41.670 --> 07:44.290
I heard from an A.A. friend
this morning.

07:44.290 --> 07:46.670
Thatcher has
acute myeloid leukemia.

07:48.460 --> 07:50.960
He's in hospice, Meredith.

07:50.960 --> 07:52.880
He has only a few weeks
to live.

07:57.460 --> 08:00.920
Meredith?
Huh? Yes?

08:00.920 --> 08:02.120
Did you hear what I said?

08:02.120 --> 08:03.830
Yes.

08:03.830 --> 08:05.290
Thatcher is dying.

08:05.290 --> 08:07.580
I got it. Thank you.

08:09.880 --> 08:11.880
[ Door opens and closes ]

08:24.880 --> 08:26.920
You guys know someone
named Betty?

08:26.920 --> 08:29.670
[ Nilu's "Hummingbird" plays ]

08:29.670 --> 08:35.620
♪♪

08:35.620 --> 08:41.880
♪♪

08:41.880 --> 08:43.710
Excuse me. Excuse me.

08:43.710 --> 08:46.380
♪♪

08:46.380 --> 08:48.880
Betty! Betty!

08:48.880 --> 08:50.500
Betty!

08:50.500 --> 08:53.000
Oh. Um, I'm --
I'm sorry.

08:55.250 --> 08:56.790
Hey.

08:56.790 --> 08:58.380
You want to see
what I'm working on?

08:58.380 --> 08:59.790
Mm-hmm.

08:59.790 --> 09:01.120
[ Pen clicking ]

09:01.120 --> 09:07.040
♪♪

09:07.040 --> 09:08.710
Mer?

09:08.710 --> 09:11.380
[ Sighs ] My father's dying.
♪ It happens unexpectedly ♪

09:11.380 --> 09:14.380
♪ Sometimes ♪
Oh, my God.

09:14.380 --> 09:15.330
Of what?

09:15.330 --> 09:17.960
AML.

09:17.960 --> 09:19.500
You want to talk about it?
No.

09:19.500 --> 09:21.420
♪ A reminiscing ♪

09:21.420 --> 09:22.710
[ Chair rolling ]

09:22.710 --> 09:25.960
♪ About things in life ♪

09:25.960 --> 09:27.960
He doesn't even know
you exist.

09:27.960 --> 09:30.290
That's how much of a not-father
he's been to me.

09:30.290 --> 09:32.040
He doesn't even know
I have a sister.

09:32.040 --> 09:34.210
I mean, I was sort of
a love-child situation --

09:34.210 --> 09:36.170
And now he's dying, and he
doesn't even tell me that.

09:36.170 --> 09:37.250
Who told you?

09:37.250 --> 09:39.250
Richard, of all people.

09:39.250 --> 09:41.250
What are you gonna do?

09:41.250 --> 09:42.710
I don't know.

09:42.710 --> 09:44.210
I'm supposed to grieve.

09:44.210 --> 09:45.290
[ Door opens ]

09:45.290 --> 09:49.000
Hello.
Brought you a little recharge.

09:49.000 --> 09:51.000
Get it? Coffee,
rechargeable hearts.

09:51.000 --> 09:52.210
Yeah.
Pretty solid.
Hey.

09:52.210 --> 09:54.920
You have a deadbeat dad,
don't you?

09:54.920 --> 09:57.500
That's a weird segue,
but, essentially, yeah.

09:57.500 --> 09:59.790
How would you feel
if you found out he was dying?

10:01.420 --> 10:03.170
What's he dying of?

10:03.170 --> 10:04.750
-No.
-No, no. No, no.

10:06.620 --> 10:08.250
Oh, well, I mean, I'd be

10:08.250 --> 10:10.290
conflicted about it, sure.

10:10.290 --> 10:12.750
Would you want
to say goodbye?

10:12.750 --> 10:15.540
That I don't know.

10:15.540 --> 10:17.960
That's not helpful.

10:17.960 --> 10:20.670
♪ When I'm alone ♪

10:20.670 --> 10:22.670
♪ The places I go ♪

10:22.670 --> 10:23.880
Hmm?
[ Door opens ]

10:23.880 --> 10:26.920
Her deadbeat dad
actually is dying.

10:28.500 --> 10:30.670
He and his little friend
were trying to climb the fence,

10:30.670 --> 10:32.290
which he knows
he's not supposed to do.

10:32.290 --> 10:33.670
I'm sorry.

10:33.670 --> 10:36.670
I climbed my share of fences
when I was a kid, too.

10:36.670 --> 10:38.290
Can I see this?

10:38.290 --> 10:40.420
Now, uh,
can you feel this?

10:40.420 --> 10:42.040
Yeah? Wiggle your
fingers for me, J.J.

10:42.040 --> 10:43.210
[ Gasps ]

10:43.210 --> 10:44.330
Hmm.

10:44.330 --> 10:46.120
What do you think,
newbie?

10:46.120 --> 10:48.210
My guess
is a humerus fracture.

10:48.210 --> 10:50.420
Good guess.
You're a natural.

10:50.420 --> 10:52.210
We're gonna get you
an X-ray, okay, bud?

10:52.210 --> 10:54.540
Take him up to radiology and
grab me when his results are up.

10:54.540 --> 10:56.880
[ Excitedly ] Am I gonna
get to wear a cast?

10:56.880 --> 10:58.670
Hunter wore a cast
last year,

10:58.670 --> 11:00.500
and everyone drew
funny pictures on it.

11:00.500 --> 11:02.580
I'll even let you
pick the color.

11:02.580 --> 11:05.170
Yes!

11:05.170 --> 11:07.920
Poor Roberta.
Three livers in one year?

11:07.920 --> 11:10.080
That's crappy luck.

11:10.080 --> 11:11.620
Sometimes that's how
the dice land.

11:13.040 --> 11:14.420
What the hell?

11:14.420 --> 11:16.250
Parker? Ned Billings?!

11:16.250 --> 11:17.960
We resected
his bowel yesterday.

11:17.960 --> 11:19.330
He was fine!
What happened?

11:19.330 --> 11:21.420
He coded.
Webber thinks he threw a clot.

11:21.420 --> 11:24.250
I'm sorry.
[ Exhaling heavily ]

11:24.250 --> 11:25.880
Oh, man!

11:25.880 --> 11:28.710
I'll call his son.

11:28.710 --> 11:30.580
Man, he was
an organ donor, too.

11:30.580 --> 11:32.500
[ Sighs ] Well, that's
not an option now.

11:32.500 --> 11:35.580
And he was a blood match
for Roberta.

11:35.580 --> 11:37.670
Salt in the wound.

11:37.670 --> 11:40.830
Wilson, that's it.
T-- Wait.

11:40.830 --> 11:42.210
Hold on! Hold on!
Hold on! Hold on!

11:42.210 --> 11:45.380
Parker, how long ago did
Dr. Webber call time of death?

11:45.380 --> 11:47.540
Uh, seven minutes.
[ Exhales sharply ]

11:47.540 --> 11:50.500
Perfect.
Five-minute rule.

11:50.500 --> 11:52.250
Hey, Ned.

11:52.250 --> 11:54.250
Dr. Bailey, what
are you doing? He's dead!

11:54.250 --> 11:55.790
We need to reperfuse
the liver.

11:55.790 --> 11:57.790
Let's get, uh, cannulas

11:57.790 --> 11:59.540
and get an ECMO machine
set up in an O.R.
His heart stopped.

11:59.540 --> 12:02.250
His organs are useless.
Yeah. Bag him, please.

12:02.250 --> 12:04.540
Wow. Is she losing it?
Do we need to call someone?

12:04.540 --> 12:06.920
My God, Dr. Bailey,
his liver is as dead as he is!

12:06.920 --> 12:09.500
And we are gonna bring it
back to life!

12:15.830 --> 12:17.670
Go get my husband.
No. Parker,

12:17.670 --> 12:19.500
get a reperfusion machine.

12:19.500 --> 12:21.670
I've been reading these case
studies out of Europe,

12:21.670 --> 12:23.670
but I've never done one
myself.
Jo: Done what?

12:23.670 --> 12:24.880
Zombie medicine?!

12:24.880 --> 12:26.580
No, we get him on ECMO,

12:26.580 --> 12:30.250
then use a normothermic
perfusion system for the liver.

12:30.250 --> 12:32.790
We can save it,
and we can give it to Roberta.

12:32.790 --> 12:34.830
Now, help me.
So, what -- you're saying

12:34.830 --> 12:36.620
that warm perfusion will bring
the liver back to life?

12:36.620 --> 12:38.620
Like a corroded penny
dipped in acid.

12:38.620 --> 12:40.500
They've done it
multiple times.

12:40.500 --> 12:43.540
♪♪

12:43.540 --> 12:44.670
In humans!

12:44.670 --> 12:46.040
-Take over.
-Thank God!

12:47.670 --> 12:49.670
Parker,
get the reperfusion machine!

12:49.670 --> 12:50.880
Casey:
Uh, yes, ma'am.

12:50.880 --> 12:53.420
♪♪

12:53.420 --> 12:56.040
[ Indistinct conversations ]

13:00.040 --> 13:02.920
[ Conversations continue ]

13:05.880 --> 13:08.170
[ Telephone ringing ]

13:08.170 --> 13:10.380
When are you gonna let me
take you to dinner?

13:10.380 --> 13:12.670
Jo seems to think
there's something here.

13:12.670 --> 13:16.830
You know, I have a matchmaker,
and she has a list.

13:16.830 --> 13:19.880
Well, how do I
get on that list?

13:19.880 --> 13:22.460
You're not the kind of guy
on the list.

13:22.460 --> 13:24.080
And what kind of guy
am I?

13:24.080 --> 13:27.380
You know, you're like the
"in an emergency" kind of guy

13:27.380 --> 13:29.750
or "I just got some really bad
news and I can't be alone"

13:29.750 --> 13:31.330
kind of guy.
[ Laughs ]

13:31.330 --> 13:33.670
[ Laughing ]

13:33.670 --> 13:35.120
Okay.

13:35.120 --> 13:36.920
Jo will be heartbroken.

13:36.920 --> 13:39.580
Oh. What's the story
with you and Jo?

13:39.580 --> 13:42.710
Does Alex have anything
to be worried about?

13:42.710 --> 13:45.040
What's the story
with you and Alex?

13:45.040 --> 13:46.670
Does Jo have anything
to worry about?

13:46.670 --> 13:54.620
♪♪

13:57.330 --> 13:59.120
Jo: How did Ned's
family take it?

13:59.120 --> 14:03.120
Bailey: Sad, but happy some good
might come out of his death.

14:03.120 --> 14:04.750
Okay, Parker,

14:04.750 --> 14:07.540
I need you to prime
the inflow and outflow lines.

14:07.540 --> 14:09.500
Karev,
you know what to do.

14:12.830 --> 14:14.170
Good.

14:14.170 --> 14:17.170
Are you ready?
Casey: All systems go.

14:17.170 --> 14:23.880
♪♪

14:23.880 --> 14:30.750
♪♪

14:30.750 --> 14:33.290
[ Plastic crinkles ]

14:33.290 --> 14:35.040
[ Lock engages,
machine whirring ]

14:35.040 --> 14:36.460
This is so stressful.

14:36.460 --> 14:39.580
[ Chuckles ]
But good stress, pure.

14:39.580 --> 14:42.670
No "will my husband
come home tonight?" stress,

14:42.670 --> 14:44.750
no red-tape stress,

14:44.750 --> 14:49.500
just "can we save
a life or not?" stress.

14:49.500 --> 14:53.880
♪♪

14:53.880 --> 14:56.460
Oh, my God, it worked!
Aah!

14:56.460 --> 14:57.670
[ Laughing ]
It's alive.

14:57.670 --> 14:59.000
It's alive!

14:59.000 --> 15:01.880
[ Laughs ]

15:01.880 --> 15:03.380
Yeah!
[ Laughs ]

15:03.380 --> 15:05.580
It's functioning.
It's a viable liver.

15:05.580 --> 15:07.830
You fish it out
of the garbage or something?

15:07.830 --> 15:09.420
What did UNOS say?

15:09.420 --> 15:11.750
As long as the organ procurement
center approves it,

15:11.750 --> 15:13.830
then we're good to
go. It's -- It's a
directed donation.

15:15.500 --> 15:17.290
Don't forget --
the good deli.

15:17.290 --> 15:19.170
Just --
Roberta, we have a liver.

15:19.170 --> 15:22.170
It's yours.
"As long as the organ
procurement center approves it."

15:22.170 --> 15:24.330
I don't like my odds.
I'm sorry about her.

15:24.330 --> 15:26.290
She's obsessed with death.
Mm, because I'm dying.

15:26.290 --> 15:28.040
Stop it!
Stop talking like that.

15:28.040 --> 15:29.920
You know, some of us
actually want you to live.

15:29.920 --> 15:32.620
Trust me,
I want me to live, too.

15:32.620 --> 15:35.040
I'm just preparing for the
reality that I probably won't.

15:35.040 --> 15:36.420
Well, you don't
have to prepare me.

15:36.420 --> 15:38.120
I will handle it.
You're not the only one

15:38.120 --> 15:40.290
who has to be prepared,
Denise.

15:40.290 --> 15:44.040
I'm the one who's dying.
You're not dying!

15:44.040 --> 15:46.000
I'm sorry, Dr. Karev.

15:46.000 --> 15:48.250
I appreciate that you think
you have a liver for me,

15:48.250 --> 15:50.830
and I hope
that you are right,

15:50.830 --> 15:53.540
but I have lived with this
condition my entire life.

15:53.540 --> 15:56.750
I have prepared to die
young...ish.

15:56.750 --> 15:59.620
And now that I'm close to that
death and statistically unlikely

15:59.620 --> 16:03.670
to experience some magical,
stardust liver miracle,

16:03.670 --> 16:05.540
I just want to make sure
that the people I love

16:05.540 --> 16:07.920
are given the chance
to grieve me.

16:07.920 --> 16:11.000
That's not your job
to worry about.

16:11.000 --> 16:13.420
It is, D.
When my father died,

16:13.420 --> 16:17.250
I wanted to throw myself
on his casket and weep.

16:17.250 --> 16:19.120
But instead,
I wrote jokes for his eulogy

16:19.120 --> 16:20.960
to make his friends
feel better

16:20.960 --> 16:23.540
and then spent 10 years crying
at dog-food commercials

16:23.540 --> 16:27.790
because all of that grief
was still in me,

16:27.790 --> 16:31.210
and it needed
a place to go.

16:31.210 --> 16:32.960
[ Voice breaking ]
You deserve...

16:32.960 --> 16:35.710
to throw yourself
on my casket and weep...

16:35.710 --> 16:37.500
if you want to.

16:40.580 --> 16:42.500
Good speech,

16:42.500 --> 16:45.210
but this doctor's waiting to see
if you want her trash liver.

16:45.210 --> 16:47.210
[ Both laugh ]

16:50.080 --> 16:51.960
Yes, please.
Yes.

16:51.960 --> 16:54.040
But if it doesn't work --
No organ music. String quartet.

16:54.040 --> 16:55.500
Yes.

16:55.500 --> 16:57.000
[ Indistinct conversations ]

16:57.000 --> 16:58.620
Okay. Hello, everyone.

16:58.620 --> 16:59.670
Laura: Hola.

16:59.670 --> 17:01.500
Okay, kiddo,
time to take you up.

17:03.460 --> 17:05.880
You're gonna be in my surgery?
Mm-hmm.

17:05.880 --> 17:08.120
Dr. Grey and Dr. Karev and I are
gonna be there the whole time.

17:08.120 --> 17:09.880
So, you're gonna see
inside my belly?

17:09.880 --> 17:12.040
Yes, but we're gonna
fix you right up.

17:12.040 --> 17:15.420
Mom...
[ Speaking Spanish ]

17:15.420 --> 17:18.290
I'm sorry.
Do you not want me there?

17:18.290 --> 17:22.170
[ Speaking Spanish ]

17:25.500 --> 17:26.960
Um...

17:26.960 --> 17:28.500
[ Clicks tongue ]
You know what, Flor?

17:28.500 --> 17:30.580
I got a whole bunch of work
I need to do today,

17:30.580 --> 17:33.420
and Dr. Grey and Dr. Karev --
I'm their student.

17:33.420 --> 17:35.620
And I don't want them
getting distracted

17:35.620 --> 17:37.170
trying to teach me
while you're on the table.

17:37.170 --> 17:39.080
I want them focused.

17:39.080 --> 17:40.620
So, if it's okay
with you,

17:40.620 --> 17:42.250
I'm gonna sit
this one out, okay?

17:44.040 --> 17:45.710
[ Sighing ] Yeah.
It's okay with me.

17:45.710 --> 17:47.790
You got this.

17:47.790 --> 17:50.960
Okay. Gracias.

17:50.960 --> 17:53.460
[ Speaking Spanish ]

17:53.460 --> 17:55.920
Oh, hey, uh, just give them
a minute, okay?

17:55.920 --> 17:57.960
Okay, mijita, you ready?

17:59.040 --> 18:00.500
[ Quietly ] Okay.

18:00.500 --> 18:04.250
[ All praying in Spanish ]

18:04.250 --> 18:05.830
You gonna come out
for a drink tonight?

18:05.830 --> 18:07.540
I don't think so.

18:07.540 --> 18:09.290
Hot date?

18:09.290 --> 18:11.120
[ Laughing ]
What? No. Wh--

18:13.330 --> 18:14.880
What's your deal?

18:14.880 --> 18:17.790
I have no deal.

18:17.790 --> 18:19.500
You got a boyfriend
or something?

18:19.500 --> 18:21.120
I don't -- I'm not...

18:23.250 --> 18:24.960
Does it seem like I do?

18:24.960 --> 18:28.080
You seem...nervous.

18:28.080 --> 18:30.750
[ Clears throat ]

18:30.750 --> 18:31.830
Do you have a boyfriend?

18:31.830 --> 18:33.580
[ Chuckling ]
No.

18:33.580 --> 18:34.880
Fellowship year.

18:34.880 --> 18:36.670
Kind of a, uh, relationship
killer, you know?

18:36.670 --> 18:38.170
[ Exhaling ]
Oh, yeah, totally.

18:38.170 --> 18:39.880
But I'm open...

18:39.880 --> 18:40.790
to meeting someone.

18:40.790 --> 18:42.620
Cool. Very cool.

18:46.460 --> 18:48.790
[ Computer beeping ]

18:48.790 --> 18:51.540
Wait. Is that a mass?

18:51.540 --> 18:52.960
[ Sighs ]

18:55.040 --> 18:56.540
All right, I'm supposed
to be in surgery.

18:56.540 --> 18:58.580
What's up?

18:58.580 --> 19:00.210
[ Singsong voice ]
Ta-da!

19:00.210 --> 19:01.750
Yeah. It's a liver.
[ Clears throat ]

19:01.750 --> 19:03.540
Why is it a liver?
It is a liver

19:03.540 --> 19:06.670
that was once in a dead man
who is very much alive.

19:06.670 --> 19:08.960
Not -- The liver, not the man.
The man is still dead.

19:08.960 --> 19:10.540
Y-- This liver
survived a cardiac death?

19:10.540 --> 19:12.500
Yep. We brought it
back to life.

19:12.500 --> 19:14.880
[ Laughing ]
Oh, crap.

19:14.880 --> 19:16.290
I can't believe
UNOS approved this.

19:16.290 --> 19:17.750
They did not.

19:17.750 --> 19:19.330
Well, they said
that it's not up to them

19:19.330 --> 19:21.250
since it's technically
a directed donation,

19:21.250 --> 19:23.170
so we called the organ
procurement center.

19:23.170 --> 19:25.960
They said they'd get
back to us, and the
donor's family consented.

19:25.960 --> 19:27.620
Get back to you?

19:27.620 --> 19:29.960
Uh, they will get back to us
with that approval

19:29.960 --> 19:32.670
because this is
a fully functioning liver.

19:32.670 --> 19:35.170
This is a liver that
doesn't even know it's
outside of a body.

19:35.170 --> 19:38.210
[ Chuckles ]
Please tell me you didn't
promise this liver to a patient.

19:38.210 --> 19:39.920
It's functioning.
No, no, no, no, no.

19:39.920 --> 19:41.920
Shut it down.
What?

19:41.920 --> 19:43.250
No. I don't care
how cool this is.

19:43.250 --> 19:45.330
This liver is not going
into a patient.

19:45.330 --> 19:47.120
Alex, we're gonna
save a life here

19:47.120 --> 19:48.750
with a liver that would
otherwise be trash.

19:48.750 --> 19:51.290
Which is where our
standing would be with
UNOS if this goes bad.

19:51.290 --> 19:52.880
Well,
that's not gonna happen.

19:52.880 --> 19:55.080
I know -- because
you're not doing it.

19:55.080 --> 19:57.210
Shut it down.

19:58.670 --> 20:00.330
[ Sighs ]

20:08.880 --> 20:10.380
And she doesn't want me
to see inside her belly.

20:10.380 --> 20:11.920
Well, you can't blame the girl.
That's sweet.

20:11.920 --> 20:13.620
Still, I'm a little
bummed. It's a Roux-en-Y
hepaticojejunostomy.

20:13.620 --> 20:16.170
There'll be lots of chances
for lots of cool surgeries

20:16.170 --> 20:18.540
with little girls
who aren't in love with you.
[ Chuckles ]

20:18.540 --> 20:20.460
Unless -- Do they all
fall in love with you?

20:20.460 --> 20:22.620
[ Both chuckle ]

20:22.620 --> 20:26.500
I was really looking forward
to working with you, Dr. Grey.

20:26.500 --> 20:28.830
Well, there will be lots
of chances for that, too.

20:31.210 --> 20:32.540
I got to go
check on our girl.

20:32.540 --> 20:34.420
Okay.

20:36.210 --> 20:39.120
Hey, sweet pea.
How you doing?

20:39.120 --> 20:40.750
You see your guy
out there?

20:40.750 --> 20:46.920
♪♪

20:46.920 --> 20:49.670
Well, it's definitely
a humerus fracture.

20:49.670 --> 20:53.710
Okay, so, how long does he
have to be in a cast?

20:53.710 --> 20:59.710
Um, unfortunately...
we also found a mass.

20:59.710 --> 21:01.580
We don't know for sure
what it is yet --
A mass?

21:01.580 --> 21:03.790
We think it's what weakened
the bone, causing the break.

21:03.790 --> 21:06.580
We just need to do
a quick biopsy.

21:06.580 --> 21:09.790
A biopsy?

21:09.790 --> 21:12.250
Does that mean cancer?
[ Voice breaking ] Oh, my God.

21:12.250 --> 21:14.290
I cannot believe
this is happening.

21:14.290 --> 21:16.790
Oh, no.
Mom, come on.

21:16.790 --> 21:18.330
[ Crying ]
Hey, J.J., what's
your mom's name?

21:18.330 --> 21:20.040
Michelle.
Michelle, look at me.

21:20.040 --> 21:21.330
Take a breath. All right?
Okay.

21:21.330 --> 21:22.670
There's good news here.

21:22.670 --> 21:25.330
The good news is the break
brought you in early,

21:25.330 --> 21:27.920
so we can figure out what it is
and make a plan.

21:27.920 --> 21:30.460
I won't climb
fences again, Mom.

21:30.460 --> 21:32.830
I promise.
It's okay, baby.

21:36.880 --> 21:39.380
Hey.
What ya got there?

21:39.380 --> 21:42.290
Well, I wanted to bring you
lunch, but I couldn't decide,

21:42.290 --> 21:44.960
so I got you enchiladas,
no cilantro,

21:44.960 --> 21:48.620
spaghetti, no meatballs,
and then, of course...

21:48.620 --> 21:50.620
[ Chuckles ]
...that'll be our Cobb salad,
no bleu cheese.

21:50.620 --> 21:51.710
[ Both laugh ]

21:51.710 --> 21:53.170
You really didn't
have to do this.

21:53.170 --> 21:54.460
Yeah. I think I did.

21:54.460 --> 21:56.170
I know I haven't been
the best boyfriend lately,

21:56.170 --> 22:00.040
so I just wanted to let you know
that I am here for you.

22:02.420 --> 22:05.120
I appreciate that.

22:05.120 --> 22:07.420
But I cannot eat
any of this right now.

22:07.420 --> 22:09.080
What's up?
You not feeling okay?

22:09.080 --> 22:10.920
I'm feeling a little sad,

22:10.920 --> 22:14.710
with all the grief
in the air today, you know?

22:14.710 --> 22:17.420
[ Quietly ] Oh. Your mom.

22:17.420 --> 22:19.380
I'm sorry.

22:19.380 --> 22:22.170
You want to, uh,
talk about it a little bit?

22:28.040 --> 22:29.710
I really got to
get back to work.

22:32.290 --> 22:33.460
Yeah.

22:33.460 --> 22:37.380
Well, if you need anything,
I am here.

22:37.380 --> 22:39.620
Thank you.
You're welcome.

22:39.620 --> 22:41.880
And if I need some
spaghetti, do you mind?

22:41.880 --> 22:44.540
Yes, please, it's all yours.
[ Chuckling ]

22:44.540 --> 22:47.500
[ Door opens ]

22:47.500 --> 22:48.830
[ Breathes deeply ]

22:50.750 --> 22:53.960
We're almost 75% finished
with this anastomosis.

22:53.960 --> 22:56.080
Looks good, even without
Loverboy's help.

22:56.080 --> 22:58.040
He was just doing what
the patient asked him to do.
[ Chuckling ] Yeah.

22:58.040 --> 23:00.210
If I backed out of every
case where some kid
fell in love with me...

23:00.210 --> 23:03.670
Don't finish that sentence,
Evilspawn.

23:05.710 --> 23:07.540
I heard about Thatcher.
Oh. From Maggie? Or Richard?

23:07.540 --> 23:10.500
Jackson.

23:10.500 --> 23:12.830
So, you don't want
to talk about it?
I'm not
not talking about it.

23:12.830 --> 23:14.500
I'm just -- I don't know that
there's much to say.

23:14.500 --> 23:16.920
Take some time if you need it,
go see him,

23:16.920 --> 23:19.540
say goodbye,
as much time as you need.

23:19.540 --> 23:21.710
You're friends
with the chief now.
[ Laughs ]

23:21.710 --> 23:23.380
Well, I don't know
that I want to see him.

23:23.380 --> 23:25.460
Okay, so, he wasn't father of
the year to you, but still --

23:25.460 --> 23:26.920
Didn't your dad
disappear on you?

23:26.920 --> 23:29.500
Yeah. But I got to say goodbye
to him before he died.

23:29.500 --> 23:31.290
And did that make
the birthday no-shows

23:31.290 --> 23:33.710
and the crying mom
on the holidays go away?

23:33.710 --> 23:36.540
Did having five minutes with him
after a lifetime of nothing

23:36.540 --> 23:39.210
make you feel better?
Suction.

23:39.210 --> 23:40.420
I opened the door
for him.

23:40.420 --> 23:42.500
I gave him
a piece of my liver.

23:42.500 --> 23:44.210
I opened the door for him
to get to know me.

23:44.210 --> 23:45.620
He did not walk
through it.

23:45.620 --> 23:46.920
The only time
we ever spent together

23:46.920 --> 23:49.290
was when Lexie forced us
to be together.

23:49.290 --> 23:51.120
And then when she died,
he completely disappeared.

23:51.120 --> 23:53.500
So, I don't really need
to grieve him

23:53.500 --> 23:56.380
because he's been a ghost
for years.

23:56.380 --> 23:58.210
You know,
our entire career exists

23:58.210 --> 23:59.960
to prevent people
from dying.

23:59.960 --> 24:01.500
They give out awards
for it.

24:01.500 --> 24:04.080
And here's Flor's family
celebrating death.

24:04.080 --> 24:05.540
They're not
celebrating death.

24:05.540 --> 24:06.830
They're celebrating
the dead.

24:06.830 --> 24:08.500
And inviting them to come back
for a visit.

24:08.500 --> 24:10.380
Maybe they didn't see them
before they died.

24:10.380 --> 24:12.710
[ Laughing ] Oh, you are not
as clever as you think you are.

24:12.710 --> 24:14.880
I disagree.
[ Metal clinking ]

24:14.880 --> 24:16.500
It's such crap.
Just 'cause he's chief,

24:16.500 --> 24:18.790
he can tell me what I can
and can't do at work?

24:18.790 --> 24:21.000
Sort of what
a chief does, yeah.

24:21.000 --> 24:23.670
Whatever. He bends his
rules all the time to
save his own patients.

24:23.670 --> 24:25.670
Yeah, but he's the chief.

24:25.670 --> 24:27.830
Okay, are you my friend
or his?

24:27.830 --> 24:29.670
Speaking of your friends,

24:29.670 --> 24:31.210
I asked Grey out.

24:31.210 --> 24:32.790
[ Gasps ]
Yes. When's the date?

24:32.790 --> 24:34.000
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah, she rejected me,

24:34.000 --> 24:36.120
pretty brutally...
again.

24:36.120 --> 24:38.830
She did that to me, too,
for like the first two years.

24:38.830 --> 24:41.250
She's gonna come around.
[ Bag rips ]

24:41.250 --> 24:42.880
Dr. Lincoln.
Oh.

24:42.880 --> 24:45.750
J.J.'s biopsy results.

24:45.750 --> 24:47.580
[ Quietly ] Damn it.

24:47.580 --> 24:48.620
[ Sighs ]

24:48.620 --> 24:50.000
Osteosarcoma.

24:50.000 --> 24:52.920
Isn't that what you --
Yeah. It is.

24:52.920 --> 24:55.000
Betty?!

24:55.000 --> 24:57.620
It's getting late.
She can't be out
there all night.

24:57.620 --> 24:59.710
Damn it, Betty! I
never should have
let her go to school.

24:59.710 --> 25:01.580
Should we call
the police?
No.
Yes.

25:01.580 --> 25:04.210
Listen, she's a teenager.
Teenagers do these things.

25:04.210 --> 25:06.380
Are you kidding me?!
Do you know how many times
my mom would freak out

25:06.380 --> 25:07.830
when I was just down the street
at my girlfriend's house?

25:07.830 --> 25:09.460
Yeah, and when I was 15,

25:09.460 --> 25:10.670
my mom called the police,
looking for me,

25:10.670 --> 25:12.420
and when she found me,
I was high on pills,

25:12.420 --> 25:13.880
about to jump off
my friend's roof.

25:13.880 --> 25:16.000
Fine. You're right.
I'm just --
Yeah, Betty is not "fine"

25:16.000 --> 25:17.790
because Betty
is not a normal teenager!

25:17.790 --> 25:19.790
She's not like you, Owen!
She is like me!

25:19.790 --> 25:21.880
And if my mom had not called
the police that day

25:21.880 --> 25:24.580
and if the police had
not found me, I would
be very dead right now!

25:27.500 --> 25:30.170
[ Sighs ]

25:30.170 --> 25:32.420
I'm sorry.

25:32.420 --> 25:34.080
[ Voice breaking ]
I need a meeting.

25:34.080 --> 25:36.120
Okay. I'll take you,
and then I'll pick up Leo.

25:36.120 --> 25:37.920
What if Betty comes back?

25:37.920 --> 25:39.380
Well, I-I can stay here.

25:41.880 --> 25:44.000
I mean -- I mean, in case she
comes back, I-I-I could be here.

25:47.830 --> 25:49.710
[ Door opens ]

25:49.710 --> 25:51.750
She's scared.
No, I-I know. I know.
[ Sighs ]

25:54.540 --> 25:56.250
[ Door closes ]

25:56.250 --> 25:58.170
And I'm pregnant
with your baby, Owen.

25:58.170 --> 25:59.710
[ Sighs heavily ]

25:59.710 --> 26:02.170
[ Exhales sharply ]

26:03.210 --> 26:05.170
[ Sighs ]

26:05.170 --> 26:07.380
[ Siren wails in distance ]

26:09.210 --> 26:11.210
[ Indistinct whispering ]
Doctor's here, guys.

26:11.210 --> 26:12.620
[ Speaking Spanish ]
Doctor's here.

26:12.620 --> 26:15.620
She's doing great.
She's in the PACU.

26:15.620 --> 26:17.330
Oh, thank God.

26:17.330 --> 26:19.710
Can we see her?
Yeah, of course.
I'll take you.

26:19.710 --> 26:21.620
Mateo: Come on, guys.
Hey, we can finally eat.

26:21.620 --> 26:24.120
Let's go.

26:24.120 --> 26:26.210
Thank you.
Okay.

26:27.670 --> 26:29.080
Gracias.

26:31.080 --> 26:35.750
May I?
[ Chuckling ] Oh, of course.

26:35.750 --> 26:36.920
Who are all these people?

26:39.040 --> 26:43.040
That is my husband, Oscar,
Laura's father.

26:43.040 --> 26:44.830
And this is Johnny,
my son,

26:44.830 --> 26:48.420
and that is my mamá, Lupita,
and my sister, Luisa.

26:48.420 --> 26:49.880
I'm sorry.

26:49.880 --> 26:51.540
Oh, don't be.

26:52.920 --> 26:54.670
They are here with us now.

26:56.620 --> 26:58.420
And this is for you.

26:58.420 --> 27:00.120
Oh, marigolds
are beautiful.

27:00.120 --> 27:02.210
It is said
that they help guide

27:02.210 --> 27:04.620
our ancestors' spirits
back to us.

27:04.620 --> 27:08.210
The veil between our world
and the spirit world

27:08.210 --> 27:10.120
is very thin.

27:10.120 --> 27:12.960
The marigolds, the photos,
the mementos --

27:12.960 --> 27:15.120
they help guide them
to us.

27:15.120 --> 27:23.580
♪♪

27:23.580 --> 27:25.120
[ Sighs ]

27:25.120 --> 27:26.330
[ Phone clicks ]

27:26.330 --> 27:28.290
♪♪

27:28.290 --> 27:31.120
Hey. You paged me?
Yeah. I did.

27:31.120 --> 27:32.790
The organ procurement center
called.

27:32.790 --> 27:36.830
Our directed organ donation
has been approved.

27:36.830 --> 27:38.580
Are you serious?

27:38.580 --> 27:41.170
I want you to book an O.R.
and prep Roberta.

27:41.170 --> 27:43.580
But the liver -- Alex told us to
shut down the perfusion machine.

27:43.580 --> 27:46.420
It's dead.

27:46.420 --> 27:47.880
[ Gasps ]

27:47.880 --> 27:50.290
The liver is alive.

27:50.290 --> 27:54.460
And as a result, Roberta will be
for many years to come.

27:54.460 --> 27:57.080
I don't know if Alex
will forgive me for this.

27:57.080 --> 27:59.620
If Roberta dies
and you could have saved her,

27:59.620 --> 28:01.420
you'll never
forgive yourself.

28:03.460 --> 28:05.120
[ Sighs ]

28:11.670 --> 28:13.960
My father was an English
professor.
Really? Where?

28:13.960 --> 28:15.670
Do you have a relationship
with your father?
Well...

28:15.670 --> 28:19.170
Why is it that the people who
created us get all the credit?

28:19.170 --> 28:20.920
Well, I --
Just because they accomplished

28:20.920 --> 28:23.420
the most basic of human
biological functions,

28:23.420 --> 28:25.080
they get a holiday
named after them?

28:25.080 --> 28:26.500
And then we're tortured
with guilt

28:26.500 --> 28:28.250
if we don't want to have
a relationship with them.

28:28.250 --> 28:31.250
If he wasn't a father to me,
why do I owe him?

28:31.250 --> 28:34.330
And why is it the child
who always has to forgive?

28:34.330 --> 28:36.790
"Because she's your mother.
Because he's your father."

28:36.790 --> 28:38.960
You know what?
I am so done

28:38.960 --> 28:41.710
feeling bad
about not feeling bad.

28:41.710 --> 28:44.580
I mean, it's sad when
somebody dies, and
I wish him peace,

28:44.580 --> 28:46.880
but I will not put myself
or my children

28:46.880 --> 28:48.420
through another death

28:48.420 --> 28:50.750
just to make him
feel better.
Mm-hmm.

28:50.750 --> 28:52.000
So, you understand?

28:54.080 --> 28:57.580
It looks like a telangiectatic
subtype of osteosarcoma.

28:57.580 --> 28:59.790
What does that even mean?
It's a tumor that actually --

28:59.790 --> 29:02.790
Wait. So, it is cancer?
Oh, my God, no.

29:02.790 --> 29:04.250
Mom?
Michelle, it --

29:04.250 --> 29:07.380
[ Crying ] Oh, God, no, no.
Mom? Mom?

29:07.380 --> 29:09.210
Why don't we step outside
and talk about this?

29:09.210 --> 29:12.670
[ Sobbing ]
Oh, my God.

29:12.670 --> 29:15.790
[ Sobs ] No.

29:15.790 --> 29:17.620
Shh.
I know. I'm sorry.

29:17.620 --> 29:20.250
I'm a terrible mother.
I...
No, you're not, but...

29:20.250 --> 29:22.790
Oh, my God.
...what you are is --
You're scared.

29:22.790 --> 29:24.790
And I'm telling you,
you don't have to be.

29:24.790 --> 29:26.380
Oh, G-- But you can't
promise me that, okay?

29:26.380 --> 29:28.710
I can't promise.

29:28.710 --> 29:31.000
But I did have this same tumor
when I was a kid --

29:31.000 --> 29:33.040
same exact tumor.

29:33.040 --> 29:35.080
Mine was on my femur,
and it was bigger.

29:35.080 --> 29:36.670
We caught it later
than we caught J.J.'s.

29:36.670 --> 29:38.670
We treated it,
and look at me.

29:38.670 --> 29:41.040
I'm here, Michelle.
I'm alive.

29:41.040 --> 29:42.920
So, you had it?

29:42.920 --> 29:44.330
And you survived it?

29:44.330 --> 29:46.670
Unless I'm a ghost.
[ Chuckles ]

29:46.670 --> 29:48.500
[ Sighs ]

29:48.500 --> 29:51.000
He's gonna be so scared.
[ Sighs ]

29:51.000 --> 29:53.460
Yeah, there's gonna be
scary moments, for sure.

29:53.460 --> 29:55.620
For me, the scariest part

29:55.620 --> 29:58.290
was seeing how sad
my mom was all the time.

29:58.290 --> 29:59.670
Mm-hmm.

29:59.670 --> 30:01.790
And losing my hair,
but that's 'cause --

30:01.790 --> 30:03.500
Look at this hair.
[ Laughs ]

30:03.500 --> 30:06.040
[ Laughs ]

30:06.040 --> 30:07.460
That's it. That's what
J.J. needs to see,

30:07.460 --> 30:09.250
a little bit at least,
every day.

30:09.250 --> 30:11.120
Okay. [ Sniffles ]
Okay?

30:11.120 --> 30:14.460
So, let it out and come back in
when you're ready.

30:14.460 --> 30:17.290
♪♪

30:17.290 --> 30:18.580
[ Sighs ]

30:18.580 --> 30:21.420
So, after your surgery,
we're gonna get you that cast.

30:21.420 --> 30:24.250
What are you thinking?
Blue? Green? Pink?

30:24.250 --> 30:27.580
Am I gonna lose my hair
and be bald like my grandpa?

30:27.580 --> 30:30.790
You might for a while,
but it'll grow back.

30:30.790 --> 30:32.460
Won't I look weird?

30:37.080 --> 30:38.290
I don't know.

30:42.040 --> 30:43.290
Does this look weird?
[ Laughs ]

30:43.290 --> 30:44.790
Levi: Oh, wow.
[ Chuckles ]

30:46.290 --> 30:47.790
How about that?
[ Laughs ]

30:47.790 --> 30:48.710
Weird?
[ Laughs ]

30:48.710 --> 30:50.790
Here, you want to give it a try?
Come on.
[ Giggles ]

30:50.790 --> 30:52.540
Go ahead. Right there, buddy.
Wait! Wait, wait, wait!

30:52.540 --> 30:54.880
No, don't cut it.
It's too beautiful.

30:54.880 --> 30:55.790
[ Laughing ]
Give me those.

30:55.790 --> 30:58.920
[ Laughter ]

31:03.420 --> 31:05.210
Okay. Just secure
that last stitch.

31:05.210 --> 31:10.080
♪♪

31:10.080 --> 31:11.960
[ Sighing ] Okay.

31:11.960 --> 31:14.460
♪♪

31:14.460 --> 31:17.920
[ Soft whooshing, heart beats ]

31:17.920 --> 31:19.580
Blood flow sounds good.

31:19.580 --> 31:23.330
And we have liftoff,
people!

31:23.330 --> 31:24.960
[ Laughter, applause ]

31:24.960 --> 31:29.210
This liver is fully functioning
in this recipient.

31:29.210 --> 31:31.170
We did it! [ Laughs ]

31:31.170 --> 31:32.880
We really did.

31:32.880 --> 31:36.500
Look at that. Whoo!
[ Both laugh ]

31:36.500 --> 31:40.210
Oh...wow.

31:40.210 --> 31:43.170
Oh...nice.

31:43.170 --> 31:44.670
[ Chuckles ]

31:51.750 --> 31:54.000
Flowers, too?
This is getting
a little silly.

31:54.000 --> 31:55.920
Well, they're not just flowers.
They're marigolds.

31:58.000 --> 31:59.290
The Day of the Dead.

32:01.830 --> 32:03.580
I know you're busy.

32:03.580 --> 32:05.920
I just thought you'd like
some company.

32:05.920 --> 32:08.210
Thank you.

32:08.210 --> 32:09.750
I'll leave you to it.

32:09.750 --> 32:18.000
♪♪

32:18.000 --> 32:20.170
What's your favorite food?
Um...

32:20.170 --> 32:22.420
barbecue.

32:22.420 --> 32:25.880
What's your favorite color?
Blue. Definitely.

32:25.880 --> 32:27.920
Who's your favorite band?

32:27.920 --> 32:29.670
Hmm.
That's a hard one.

32:29.670 --> 32:31.460
Radiohead?
No. The Beatles.

32:31.460 --> 32:32.710
Oh, my dad
likes The Beatles.

32:32.710 --> 32:34.920
Oh, yeah?

32:34.920 --> 32:36.120
Do you have a girlfriend?

32:36.120 --> 32:39.290
[ Chuckles ]
Uh, no, I do not.

32:39.290 --> 32:42.460
[ Laughter ]
Ay. Flor.

32:42.460 --> 32:44.080
[ Chuckles ]

32:44.080 --> 32:47.080
[ Insects chirping ]

32:47.080 --> 32:48.960
[ Door opens ]
Owen: [ Sighing ] Hey.

32:48.960 --> 32:51.540
Hey. Nothing?

32:51.540 --> 32:53.580
No.

32:53.580 --> 32:55.290
You all right?

32:55.290 --> 32:56.960
[ Groans ]

32:56.960 --> 32:58.380
[ Whispering ]
Thank you for being here.

32:58.380 --> 33:00.380
Oh, I just wish that there was
more that I could do.

33:00.380 --> 33:02.790
No. You being here
is more than enough.

33:02.790 --> 33:04.540
[ Leo coos ]

33:04.540 --> 33:06.250
Shh.

33:06.250 --> 33:08.540
Um, you know, I should've, uh --
I should've talked to you

33:08.540 --> 33:10.710
when I saw you last month
at the hospital.

33:10.710 --> 33:12.250
No, no, I should have --
I-I should -- I-I --

33:12.250 --> 33:13.670
I should have done
so many things.

33:13.670 --> 33:17.380
I should've called you.
I should've told you about Leo.

33:17.380 --> 33:20.380
For you to find out like that,
it was just...
No. It's fine.

33:20.380 --> 33:23.250
You don't -- You don't owe me
any-- No, I -- Owen...
Honestly -- Honestly,
I was embarrassed.

33:23.250 --> 33:24.880
When I saw you,
I felt embarrassed

33:24.880 --> 33:27.080
'cause I could see
how all this looked.

33:27.080 --> 33:29.920
[ Leo whimpers ]
You know?
And maybe you were right.

33:29.920 --> 33:32.540
You know, you said that I've
always been afraid to be alone.

33:32.540 --> 33:35.330
I come back from Germany,
and I proved that to be right.

33:35.330 --> 33:39.790
But Leo -- [ Chuckles ]

33:39.790 --> 33:42.460
But Leo isn't just
because I was lonely.

33:42.460 --> 33:45.960
I've wanted to be a dad
my entire life.

33:45.960 --> 33:47.540
I mean, you know that.

33:47.540 --> 33:48.540
I know.
[ Leo whimpers ]

33:48.540 --> 33:49.710
Hmm.

33:49.710 --> 33:53.830
Then Leo turned into
Leo and Betty and --

33:53.830 --> 33:57.040
and then Amelia.

33:57.040 --> 34:02.000
[ Whimpering continues ]

34:02.000 --> 34:03.920
Owen?
Hmm?

34:06.790 --> 34:08.290
Are you happy?

34:09.750 --> 34:11.380
[ Leo crying ]

34:13.880 --> 34:15.120
Ohh, shh, shh, shh, shh.

34:15.120 --> 34:16.620
He's waking up.
I'm sorry. I got to --

34:16.620 --> 34:19.290
Oh, no. Yeah. Go.
Do your thing, yeah.

34:19.290 --> 34:22.000
Yeah, um...
Come on. Come on, little guy.

34:22.000 --> 34:24.420
I'm sorry.
[ Crying continues ]

34:24.420 --> 34:25.880
I'm gonna --
I'm gonna go.

34:25.880 --> 34:28.790
Shh, shh, shh,
shh, shh, shh.

34:28.790 --> 34:31.040
[ Leo's crying continues ]

34:39.670 --> 34:42.000
[ Crying continues ]

34:42.000 --> 34:44.920
[ Clearing throat ]

34:44.920 --> 34:46.920
[ Crying continues ]

34:58.460 --> 35:00.670
[ Telephone ringing ]

35:00.670 --> 35:02.250
[ Indistinct conversations ]

35:02.250 --> 35:05.750
[ Woman on P.A.
speaking indistinctly ]

35:05.750 --> 35:08.080
[ Sighs ]

35:08.080 --> 35:10.750
Evening.

35:10.750 --> 35:12.750
What happened there?

35:12.750 --> 35:14.880
Oh. Kid with cancer.

35:14.880 --> 35:17.670
[ Telephone rings ]

35:17.670 --> 35:19.420
[ Chuckles ]

35:19.420 --> 35:25.420
♪♪

35:25.420 --> 35:28.460
In case of emergency.

35:28.460 --> 35:30.380
Hey.

35:30.380 --> 35:31.380
Hey.

35:31.380 --> 35:32.500
I like your flower.

35:32.500 --> 35:34.540
Thanks.

35:34.540 --> 35:37.080
How was your date?
She's way out of my league.

35:37.080 --> 35:39.210
[ Both chuckle ]
How was yours?

35:39.210 --> 35:41.670
I scared him off.
[ Chuckles ]

35:41.670 --> 35:43.540
[ Breathes deeply ]

35:43.540 --> 35:44.710
[ Elevator bell dings ]

35:44.710 --> 35:52.000
♪♪

35:52.000 --> 35:53.540
I'm gonna take the stairs.

35:53.540 --> 35:55.620
♪♪

35:55.620 --> 35:57.620
[ Clears throat ]

35:57.620 --> 36:02.290
♪♪

36:02.290 --> 36:04.420
Hey.
What's up?

36:04.420 --> 36:06.210
Bailey:
The surgery was flawless.

36:06.210 --> 36:08.670
R.I.'s on ultrasound
look promising.

36:08.670 --> 36:10.670
Bilirubin levels
are decreasing.

36:10.670 --> 36:14.960
You have a fully functioning,
healthy liver, Ms. Gibbs.

36:14.960 --> 36:16.250
Jo:
So no funeral for you.

36:16.250 --> 36:19.120
[ Light laughter ]

36:19.120 --> 36:21.710
[ Sniffles ]
Denise, honey, I wanted you
to cry at my funeral.

36:21.710 --> 36:24.290
[ Laughing ] I know.

36:24.290 --> 36:25.580
I'm gonna live.

36:25.580 --> 36:27.830
I told you!
[ Laughter ]

36:30.040 --> 36:31.500
Thank you.

36:31.500 --> 36:33.670
[ Sighing and laughter ]

36:36.620 --> 36:40.500
[ Elevator bell dings ]

36:40.500 --> 36:42.120
Hey. How'd you feel today?

36:42.120 --> 36:44.170
What do you mean?
With ortho?

36:44.170 --> 36:46.330
Oh. Uh, terrific.

36:47.250 --> 36:48.790
You're a great teacher.

36:56.250 --> 37:02.830
♪♪

37:02.830 --> 37:04.120
[ Elevator bell dings ]

37:04.120 --> 37:07.500
[ Indistinct conversations ]

37:07.500 --> 37:09.750
[ Clears throat ]

37:09.750 --> 37:11.330
[ Elevator doors close ]

37:13.790 --> 37:15.500
[ Elevator bell dings ]
[ Clears throat ]

37:15.500 --> 37:21.960
♪♪

37:21.960 --> 37:23.880
Sorry. That was abrupt.

37:23.880 --> 37:26.460
I-I just had to see if --
It was perfect.

37:26.460 --> 37:30.250
The, uh, um -- When --
[ Chuckling ] The --

37:30.250 --> 37:31.580
Are you okay?

37:31.580 --> 37:33.830
That was my first time.

37:33.830 --> 37:36.670
Today.
Doing ortho...stuff.

37:36.670 --> 37:38.210
[ Chuckles ]

37:38.210 --> 37:40.040
Up until now,
I've been focusing on general,

37:40.040 --> 37:43.750
and it never really
felt right, but...

37:43.750 --> 37:45.710
I liked that.

37:45.710 --> 37:46.830
[ Chuckles ]

37:46.830 --> 37:49.250
Ortho.

37:49.250 --> 37:52.420
And you're
a really great teacher.

37:52.420 --> 37:54.500
Wait.

37:54.500 --> 37:55.620
That was your first kiss?

37:55.620 --> 37:57.920
With a...

37:57.920 --> 38:00.960
guy.
Oh. Wow.

38:00.960 --> 38:03.250
[ Stammers ]
I'm sorry, dude.

38:03.250 --> 38:05.250
If I would've known that,
I would've never --

38:05.250 --> 38:08.120
Y-You said you would teach me,
and I want to learn.

38:08.120 --> 38:11.040
Okay, look, you're cute
and nerdy and weird,

38:11.040 --> 38:15.580
and that's
usually my type, but...

38:15.580 --> 38:18.420
I've done my coming out already.
I can't go through it again.

38:18.420 --> 38:20.750
I can't teach you
how to do this.

38:20.750 --> 38:22.210
I'm sorry.

38:22.210 --> 38:23.790
[ Elevator bell dings,
doors open ]

38:23.790 --> 38:25.500
But I, uh...

38:25.500 --> 38:27.080
[ Indistinct conversations ]

38:27.080 --> 38:28.830
I thought this was
a teaching hospital!

38:32.710 --> 38:36.000
Look, I'm sorry I went
against your chief-ness,

38:36.000 --> 38:37.880
but you can't just go
around controlling
what I do in the O.R.

38:37.880 --> 38:39.290
Well, I kinda can
'cause I'm your boss.

38:39.290 --> 38:41.000
I saved a life, though.
I --

38:42.420 --> 38:44.290
Wait. Wait.
I thought we were fighting.

38:44.290 --> 38:47.620
We are, but I'm also
really turned on by
your medical genius.

38:47.620 --> 38:49.330
And the good part about this job
is I've learned

38:49.330 --> 38:50.880
I can do
two things at once.

38:54.290 --> 38:57.250
Nurse Frankie: That is
not a private space!
We can all see you!

38:57.250 --> 38:59.960
[ Chuckles ]
Sorry! [ Slaps ]

38:59.960 --> 39:01.790
[ Clears throat ]

39:01.790 --> 39:06.330
[ Moon & Sun's
"Chasing Cars" plays ]

39:06.330 --> 39:08.540
♪ Haremos todo ♪

39:08.540 --> 39:11.330
Meredith: Every religion,
every country...

39:11.330 --> 39:14.330
♪ Cada cosa ♪

39:14.330 --> 39:15.460
...every culture.

39:15.460 --> 39:19.620
♪ Por nuestra cuenta ♪

39:19.620 --> 39:22.120
♪♪

39:22.120 --> 39:24.540
♪ No necesitamos ♪

39:24.540 --> 39:27.080
Death means something different
to all of us.

39:27.080 --> 39:29.750
[ Buttons clicking ]

39:29.750 --> 39:31.750
♪ Oh, nada ♪

39:31.750 --> 39:37.290
♪ O nadie ♪

39:37.290 --> 39:42.460
♪ Si me acuesto aquí ♪

39:42.460 --> 39:45.000
Hi, Mom.
♪ Si solo me acuesto aquí ♪

39:45.000 --> 39:48.000
We all have different ideas
about how to honor the dead.

39:48.000 --> 39:54.420
♪ ¿Te acostarías conmigo
y olvidarías el mundo? ♪

39:54.420 --> 39:56.540
[ Mug thuds ]

39:56.540 --> 39:58.670
Tell me she's not dead.

39:58.670 --> 40:00.670
[ Sighs ]

40:00.670 --> 40:02.460
She is not dead.

40:02.460 --> 40:04.420
♪ No se bien ♪
Different ideas
of how to grieve.

40:04.420 --> 40:08.120
♪ Como decir ♪
It's been hard.

40:08.120 --> 40:11.250
♪ Como me siento ♪

40:11.250 --> 40:14.540
I can't say
that it hasn't been.

40:14.540 --> 40:16.250
I haven't been going
to my meetings.

40:16.250 --> 40:17.880
Different ways of moving on.

40:17.880 --> 40:20.420
♪ Esas tres palabras ♪

40:20.420 --> 40:23.210
Because it just
reminds me that --

40:23.210 --> 40:24.750
that you're gone.

40:24.750 --> 40:26.750
♪ Dicen mucho ♪

40:26.750 --> 40:29.500
♪ No son suficientes ♪

40:29.500 --> 40:32.380
Mer.

40:32.380 --> 40:34.170
Good night, Arlene.

40:34.170 --> 40:36.080
Good night, Dr. Grey.

40:36.080 --> 40:37.620
♪ Si me acuesto aquí ♪

40:37.620 --> 40:41.330
Well, I may not be an expert.

40:41.330 --> 40:44.960
♪ ¿Te acostarías conmigo ♪

40:44.960 --> 40:49.000
[ Dog barks ]
♪ Y olvidarías el mundo? ♪

40:49.000 --> 40:52.670
♪ Olvida lo que dijimos ♪

40:52.670 --> 40:55.210
But I do have some experience
with losing people I love.

40:55.210 --> 40:59.170
♪ Antes que seamos viejos ♪

40:59.170 --> 41:01.000
Hey.
♪ Muéstrame el jardín ♪

41:01.000 --> 41:02.670
♪ Que explota ♪

41:02.670 --> 41:08.000
♪ Dentro de mi vida ♪

41:08.000 --> 41:10.120
♪ Si me acuesto aquí ♪

41:10.120 --> 41:12.670
Can I come over?

41:12.670 --> 41:18.670
♪ ¿Te acostarías conmigo
Y olvidarías el mundo? ♪

41:24.290 --> 41:26.710
Hi.
I wanted some company.

41:26.710 --> 41:29.380
♪♪

41:29.380 --> 41:30.830
Hey!

41:30.830 --> 41:38.040
♪♪

41:38.040 --> 41:39.540
Wh-- What's happening?

41:39.540 --> 41:42.380
Mm.

41:42.380 --> 41:43.830
Hand that over.
Okay.

41:43.830 --> 41:45.080
No, no. The scissors.

41:45.080 --> 41:47.540
[ Chuckling ]
Oh. Okay.

41:47.540 --> 41:49.000
Let me just...
[ Whispering ] Thank you.

41:49.000 --> 41:50.460
Well, don't thank me yet.

41:50.460 --> 41:52.580
[ Laughs ]

41:52.580 --> 41:55.080
And I say
the right way to grieve...

41:55.080 --> 41:58.170
♪♪

41:58.170 --> 41:59.460
Be careful.
Not too much off the top.

41:59.460 --> 42:01.210
Aren't they cute together?
Mm.

42:01.210 --> 42:04.120
You seem
weirdly good at that.

42:04.120 --> 42:08.420
Well, the decade
of precision surgical training

42:08.420 --> 42:10.000
definitely comes in handy.
[ Laughter ]

42:10.000 --> 42:12.000
...is however the hell
you want.

42:12.000 --> 42:14.580
Do we have a vacuum?
No, we don't have a vacuum!

42:14.580 --> 42:17.210
-Do you --
-Why do I even ask?

42:17.210 --> 42:18.460
[ Laughter ]

42:18.460 --> 42:19.880
Do we have a...

42:19.880 --> 42:21.750
[ Laughter ]

